<h1>You already love the outdoors, we&#8217;ll help you take it up a notch</h1>

<!-- BYLINE -->
</mj-text><mj-table><tr style="border-top:1px solid #fcd232;border-bottom:1px solid #fcd232;text-align:left;"><td style="padding: 6px 3px;width:50px;"><img style="width:48px;height:48px;border:1px solid #fcd232;border-radius:50%; padding:0;" width="48px" height="48px" align="center" src="https://lede-admin.coloradosun.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/15/2018/08/Jason.jpg?resize=96,96"/></td><td style="padding: 6px;"><strong>Jason Blevins</strong><br /><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/author/jason-blevins/?pico=clean" target="_blank"><em><span style="font-size:12px;">Outdoors/Business Reporter</span></em></a></td></tr></mj-table>
<mj-image src="https://lede-admin.coloradosun.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/15/2021/02/20210207-DPSP-75.jpg?resize=800,500" href="https://coloradosun.com/confirmation-outsider-trial/?pico=clean" target="_blank"/><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>Colorado Sun reporter Jason Blevins skis through the Cameron Peaks Fire burn scar while accompanying Diamond Peaks Ski Patrol members on a duty day near Montgomery Pass, Feb. 6, 2021. (William Cotton, Special to The Colorado Sun)</em></span></p>
&nbsp;
<p style="line-height:24px;"><span style="font-size:48px;line-height:12px;">R</span>&nbsp;emember when outdoor recreation was stuck at the kid&#8217;s table? I do.</p>

<p>While federal land managers negotiated with lumber barons and energy companies, the outdoor recreation industry waited, hoping it would someday get a chance to participate in national discussions around public lands and economic development. Not even a decade ago, outdoor recreation was a diversion; it was the fun you had outside the day job.</p>

<p>Today the outdoor recreation economy is a<a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2020/02/07/jessica-whal-outdoor-recreation-q-a/?pico=clean"> political, economic and cultural juggernaut</a>. The federal government&#8217;s economic numbers show outdoor recreation eclipsing<a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2021/11/10/outdoor-recreation-economic-contribution-gdp-2020-pandemic/?pico=clean"> the nation&#8217;s fossil fuels industry</a>. In Colorado, outdoor adventurers and the businesses that support them make a <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2022/04/04/conor-hall-outdoor-recreation-question/?pico=clean">$10 billion annual impact</a>.</p>

<p>Here at The Sun, we closely follow outdoor recreation, not only the fun stuff (obviously!) but the businesses, economic growth, environmental impacts and cultural transformation that comes with a focus on adventure in Colorado&#8217;s natural, untrammeled places. The weekly Outsider newsletter —<a target="_blank"  href="https://pico.link/thecoloradosun/offer?id=CheckoutWizard_thecoloradosun&amp;short_code=theoutsider"> sign up here</a> — keeps tabs on this evolving industry, with <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2021/10/27/colorado-avalanche-backcountry-fatalities-caic/?pico=clean">early peeks</a> at coming stories, subscriber-only articles and glimpses inside the reporting we do for you.</p>

<p>With your support, The Sun will keep shining a light on how the growing outdoor recreation industry influences and impacts our state and communities. We hope you&#8217;ll come along for the ride.</p>

<p>-j</p>

